  "prompt": "The prime factorization of intezer N is A x A x B x C, where A, B and C are all distinct prine intezers. How many factors does N have?",
  "response": "To determine the number of factors of the integer \\( N \\) based on its prime factorization, we start from the given information.\n\nThe prime factorization of \\( N \\) is:\n\\[\nN = A^2 \\times B^1 \\times C^1\n\\]\nwhere \\( A, B, \\) and \\( C \\) are distinct prime integers.\n\nTo find the total number of factors of \\( N \\), we can use the following formula:\n\nIf the prime factorization of a number is given by:\n\\[\nN = p_1^{e_1} \\times p_2^{e_2} \\times \\cdots \\times p_k^{e_k}\n\\]\nwhere \\( p_1, p_2, \\ldots, p_k \\) are distinct prime factors and \\( e_1, e_2, \\ldots, e_k \\) are their respective positive integer exponents, then the total number of factors \\( d(N) \\) of \\( N \\) is given by:\n\\[\nd(N) = (e_1 + 1)(e_2 + 1) \\cdots (e_k + 1)\n\\]\n\nIn our case, we have:\n- \\( A \\) has an exponent of 2 (i.e., \\( e_1 = 2 \\))\n- \\( B \\) has an exponent of 1 (i.e., \\( e_2 = 1 \\))\n- \\( C \\) has an exponent of 1 (i.e., \\( e_3 = 1 \\))\n\nThus, we apply the formula:\n\\[\nd(N) = (2 + 1)(1 + 1)(1 + 1)\n\\]\n\nCalculating each term:\n- \\( 2 + 1 = 3 \\)\n- \\( 1 + 1 = 2 \\)\n- \\( 1 + 1 = 2 \\)\n\nNow substituting these values into the formula:\n\\[\nd(N) = 3 \\times 2 \\times 2\n\\]\n\nCalculating the product:\n\\[\nd(N) = 3 \\times 2 = 6\n\\]\n\\[\nd(N) = 6 \\times 2 = 12\n\\]\n\nTherefore, the total number of factors of \\( N \\) is:\n\\[\n\\boxed{12}\n\\]",
